export const sections: SectionHtml[] = [
 { "anchor": "s4-1", "html": "<p>Every seriously funded compact fusion design assumes a magnet conductor whose design space is not yet computable. Above 20 T, the only available option is REBCO (rare-earth barium copper oxide) coated tape — &quot;HTS is the only available choice (REBCO),&quot; per MIT's fusion-magnet review — and the record 20 T large-bore magnet that Commonwealth Fusion Systems and MIT demonstrated in September 2021 runs on it.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"46\">[46]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"116\">[116]</sup> DOE's Milestone-Based Fusion Development Program — eight companies, <span class=\"math\">$46 M committed against $</span>415 M authorized — is built on high-temperature-superconducting (HTS) magnet technology.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"48\">[48]</sup> One commercial analysis projects the fusion-HTS segment growing from ~<span class=\"math\">$1.8 B (2025) to ~$</span>14.3 B (2034), a single-analyst figure I treat as order-of-magnitude only.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"37\">[37]</sup> Grid hardware follows: Shanghai's kilometer-class 35 kV HTS cable has operated since end-2021.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"117\">[117]</sup></p>\n<p>I open the class chapters here because superconductors sharpen this paper's thesis in both directions: value certified by programs; errors spanning the taxonomy from qualitative ground-state failure (cuprates) to 10–15% quantitative overshoot (hydrides); and the worst fabrication record in materials science, which makes verified simulation a credibility instrument, not merely a design tool (§4.4). Qualitative failure first.</p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s4-2-1", "html": "<p>Undoped La<span class=\"math\">$_2$</span>CuO<span class=\"math\">$_4$</span>, parent of the highest-<span class=\"math\">$T_c$</span> ambient-pressure family, is the cleanest case of taxonomy mode 1 (§3.2). Experiment shows an antiferromagnetic (AFM) charge-transfer insulator with a ~1.3–2 eV gap; plain DFT (LSDA/PBE, <span class=\"math\">$U=0$</span>) returns a <strong>metallic, non-magnetic</strong> ground state — wrong in kind, not degree.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"41\">[41]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"118\">[118]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"79\">[79]</sup> The standard remedy is empirical: DFT+<span class=\"math\">$U$</span> gives gaps of ~0.2, 1.4, and 2 eV at <span class=\"math\">$U$</span> = 2, 6, and 8 eV, Cu moments wandering 0.21–0.61 <span class=\"math\">$\\mu_B$</span> — the right answer only at a tuned parameter.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"79\">[79]</sup> Imposing AFM order on LDA still leaves a metal; LDA+DMFT opens a 1.5–1.8 eV gap.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"119\">[119]</sup> Across 15+ density-functional approximations, LSDA and PBE fail to stabilize AFM order, SCAN lands inside experiment, and hybrid HSE06 overshoots to ~3 eV.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"41\">[41]</sup> Functional shopping moves the error without removing it: a Mott/charge-transfer insulator is a non-single-particle state, and semilocal functionals carry self-interaction error exactly where localized <span class=\"math\">$d$</span> states dominate.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"120\">[120]</sup> An MLIP trained on PBE-class labels inherits the wrong ground state before fitting begins (§3.1).</p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s4-2-2", "html": "<p>For phonon-mediated superconductors, theory at least has an equation to solve; for cuprates, nickelates, and Fe-based materials it does not. Boeri's 2019 review states that &quot;ab-initio approaches are still far from being predictive,&quot; and that without a quantitative pairing theory &quot;it is at the moment impossible to formulate reliable predictions of <span class=\"math\">$T_c$</span>.&quot;<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"9\">[9]</sup> Valenti's 2021 roadmap chapter is equally blunt: prediction &quot;requires a description beyond conventional DFT in order to properly include correlation effects.&quot;<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"21\">[21]</sup> The one accuracy ceiling — 5–10% on <span class=\"math\">$T_c$</span> from fully anisotropic Migdal–Eliashberg or superconducting DFT — applies only to conventional materials.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"9\">[9]</sup> In May 2025 the first charge-self-consistent cluster-DMFT+DFT calculation on multilayer cuprates reproduced the layer-count dependence of <span class=\"math\">$T_c$</span> and superexchange <span class=\"math\">$J$</span> trends, bringing first-principles cuprate prediction &quot;within reach&quot; — but a flagship computation is not a funnel stage.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"83\">[83]</sup> Nickelates sit behind the same wall: La<span class=\"math\">$_3$</span>Ni<span class=\"math\">$_2$</span>O<span class=\"math\">$_7$</span> reaches ~80 K only above ~15 GPa and demands orbital-selective DFT+DMFT/GW+DMFT treatments.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"121\">[121]</sup></p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s4-2-3", "html": "<p>The hydrides are where ab initio screening genuinely works — structure prediction preceded discovery for both H<span class=\"math\">$_3$</span>S and LaH<span class=\"math\">$_{10}$</span><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"122\">[122]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"123\">[123]</sup> — and they are still wrong where it matters: the phonon layer. For H<span class=\"math\">$_3$</span>S at 200 GPa, the harmonic approximation gives an electron-phonon coupling constant <span class=\"math\">$\\lambda \\approx 2.64$</span>; the nonperturbative anharmonic treatment (stochastic self-consistent harmonic approximation, SSCHA) suppresses it by 30%, to <span class=\"math\">$\\lambda \\approx 1.84$</span> — the harmonic value is ~43% too high.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"8\">[8]</sup> The failure is structural before numerical: harmonic spectra of the high-symmetry H<span class=\"math\">$_3$</span>S and LaH<span class=\"math\">$_{10}$</span> phases contain large imaginary instabilities — these are not even minima of the classical Born–Oppenheimer surface — and only the quantum Hessians are positive.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"124\">[124]</sup> Quantum fluctuations likewise stabilize LaH<span class=\"math\">$_{10}$</span>'s <span class=\"math\">$Fm\\bar{3}m$</span> phase below the 230 GPa classical distortion threshold.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"125\">[125]</sup> The <span class=\"math\">$T_c$</span> consequences are measurable: harmonic predictions of 274–286 K (210 GPa) and 288 K (200 GPa) overshot the measured 250–260 K (170–190 GPa, two groups) by ~10–15%.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"126\">[126]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"123\">[123]</sup> YH<span class=\"math\">$_{10}$</span> is the cautionary tail: predicted at 305–326 K (250 GPa) in 2017, never synthesized, re-estimated at ~267 K in a later doctoral-thesis analysis (single-source; flagged).<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"126\">[126]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"127\">[127]</sup> Practitioners put typical hydride <span class=\"math\">$T_c$</span> errors at 10–15%, yet YH<span class=\"math\">$_6$</span>'s measured upper critical field exceeds theory 2–2.5-fold.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"128\">[128]</sup></p>\n<div class=\"casebox\">\n<p><strong>Box 4.1 — Anatomy of a hydride-prediction pipeline: where the compute goes.</strong> The honest cost ledger comes from NIST's JARVIS workflow (Wines &amp; Choudhary, <em>Materials Futures</em> 2024): screening &gt;900 hydrides at 0–500 GPa took ~11,500 core-hours of DFT — ~7% for structural relaxation, and <strong>93% of the computational time for density-functional-perturbation-theory (DFPT) calculations of the electron-phonon coupling (EPC)</strong> — the step that sets <span class=\"math\">$\\lambda$</span>, the logarithmic phonon average <span class=\"math\">$\\omega_{\\log}$</span>, and hence <span class=\"math\">$T_c$</span>; the yield was 122 dynamically stable structures with <span class=\"math\">$T_c &gt; 39$</span> K.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"129\">[129]</sup> Note what the 93% does <em>not</em> buy: harmonic-level DFPT-EPC on a 2×2×2 q-grid — the anharmonic corrections of §4.2.3 were not performed.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"129\">[129]</sup> Anharmonic escalation is the real bottleneck: SSCHA minimization requires ab initio energies, forces, and stresses on stochastic ensembles of &quot;several hundreds or thousands of configurations&quot; per structure.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"130\">[130]</sup> Practitioner estimates put a 50–100-candidate screen at ~1 year of computation, against 1–2 years for a single diamond-anvil-cell experiment.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"128\">[128]</sup> Collapsing the EPC/SSCHA block — by DFPT surrogate or anharmonic MLIP — turns a year-scale serial cost into a filtering step.</p>\n</div>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s4-2-4", "html": "<p>MLIPs enter this class with three strikes. First, systematic PES softening (scoreboard Row 2): universal potentials (M3GNet, CHGNet, MACE-MP-0) underpredict energy and force curvature from near-equilibrium training bias, and softened phonons corrupt exactly the two quantities that set hydride <span class=\"math\">$T_c$</span> — <span class=\"math\">$\\omega_{\\log}$</span> and <span class=\"math\">$\\lambda$</span>.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"21\">[21]</sup> Second, coverage: pretrained universal MLIPs are &quot;less effective due to model instabilities&quot; for high-pressure hydride search, and several fail pressurized hydrogen's liquid–liquid phase transition despite low test-set errors.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"131\">[131]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"132\">[132]</sup> Third, the statistical <span class=\"math\">$T_c$</span> models inherit a data crisis: SuperCon records composition and <span class=\"math\">$T_c$</span> only — no atomic coordinates, no pressure flags — with cleaned subsets of ~13,700–16,400 entries and only ~1,600 non-superconductors.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"133\">[133]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"134\">[134]</sup> Under random cross-validation one deep model reports <span class=\"math\">$R^2 = 0.92$</span>; under leave-one-cluster-out (LOCO) validation — the honest test for finding a <em>new</em> family — errors grow sharply, and a closed-loop study found even a strong classifier failing out-of-distribution.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"135\">[135]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"136\">[136]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"137\">[137]</sup> Hydride-specific regressors carry RMSE ≈ 34–39 K (Table 4.1), in a field where one study finds only ~3% of candidates superconducting.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"138\">[138]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"135\">[135]</sup></p>\n<p><strong>Table 4.1 — Chapter error ledger: superconductors (verified figures as of 2026-07-17).</strong></p>\n<div class=\"tablewrap\"><table>\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<th>Quantity</th>\n<th>System/benchmark</th>\n<th>Method/model</th>\n<th>Predicted</th>\n<th>Reference/experimental</th>\n<th>Error magnitude</th>\n<th>Source</th>\n<th>Confidence</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>Band gap</td>\n<td>La<span class=\"math\">$_2$</span>CuO<span class=\"math\">$_4$</span>, undoped parent</td>\n<td>LSDA/PBE (<span class=\"math\">$U$</span>=0); DFT+<span class=\"math\">$U$</span> (<span class=\"math\">$U$</span>=2/6/8 eV); HSE06</td>\n<td>metallic, non-magnetic; 0.2/1.4/2 eV; ~3 eV</td>\n<td>AFM charge-transfer insulator, ~1.3–2 eV</td>\n<td>qualitative failure (metal) at <span class=\"math\">$U$</span>=0; −90% to +50% across <span class=\"math\">$U$</span> and HSE06</td>\n<td><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"41\">[41]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"79\">[79]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"119\">[119]</sup></td>\n<td>High</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"math\">$\\lambda$</span> (e-ph coupling)</td>\n<td>H<span class=\"math\">$_3$</span>S, 200 GPa</td>\n<td>harmonic DFPT vs anharmonic SSCHA</td>\n<td>2.64</td>\n<td>1.84 (SSCHA)</td>\n<td>harmonic ~43% high (30% suppression on correction)</td>\n<td><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"8\">[8]</sup></td>\n<td>High</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"math\">$T_c$</span></td>\n<td>LaH<span class=\"math\">$_{10}$</span>, ~200–210 GPa</td>\n<td>harmonic DFT + Eliashberg</td>\n<td>274–288 K</td>\n<td>250–260 K at 170–190 GPa (two groups)</td>\n<td>+10–15%</td>\n<td><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"126\">[126]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"123\">[123]</sup></td>\n<td>High</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><span class=\"math\">$T_c$</span> (ML regression)</td>\n<td>Hydride composition datasets</td>\n<td>XGBoost (ternary); neural net (binary); nested CV</td>\n<td>—</td>\n<td>DFT-computed <span class=\"math\">$T_c$</span> labels</td>\n<td>RMSE 38.5 ± 3.8 K (ternary); 33.7 K (binary)</td>\n<td><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"138\">[138]</sup></td>\n<td>High</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<p>Read down the rows, the table is the chapter in miniature. Row 1 is a <em>kind</em> error — no recalibration fixes predicting a metal for an insulating magnet, and it propagates into any MLIP trained on it. Rows 2–3 are <em>degree</em> errors with a known origin, quantum ionic motion, correctable at SSCHA cost — the very block Box 4.1 prices; the Eliashberg functional compresses ingredient errors into <span class=\"math\">$T_c$</span>, so hydride <span class=\"math\">$T_c$</span> looks deceptively healthy while its inputs are off by nearly half. Row 4 is a <em>statistical</em> error: 34–39 K RMSE exceeds the spread between record candidates (YH<span class=\"math\">$_6$</span> 224 K, LaH<span class=\"math\">$_{10}$</span> 260 K<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"139\">[139]</sup>), so composition-only regressors cannot rank the frontier they are sold to rank. Rows 1–3 rest on primary literature; row 4 on one sound benchmark paper.</p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s4-3", "html": "<p>Chapter 3 filed this class on taxonomy modes 1 (correlation) and 5 (finite-temperature) with scoreboard Rows 2, 9, and 10; the class physics sharpens the binding rows. For hydrides it is Row 2 (systematic PES softening), compounded by Row 8 (extreme conditions): a universal MLIP whose phonons run soft cannot compute <span class=\"math\">$\\omega_{\\log}$</span> or <span class=\"math\">$\\lambda$</span> at 200 GPa, and accuracy degrades from 0 to 150 GPa — documented <em>coverage</em> problems, repairable by fine-tuning rather than new architectures.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"98\">[98]</sup> Micro-dose fine-tuning halves a universal MLIP's force error with one DFT structure and reaches DFT-level vibrational spectra at ~100 frames; a single study reports curvature-targeted phonon fine-tuning (PFT) cutting phonon-property errors by 55% on average.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"21\">[21]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"87\">[87]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"88\">[88]</sup> An anharmonicity-aware hydride MLIP — trained on SSCHA ensembles at pressure, curvature-corrected at the Hessian level — is the instrument that collapses Box 4.1's 93% block — no foundation-model budget required. For cuprates the binding rows are Rows 9 and 10 (missing electronic degrees of freedom; the reference-functional ceiling). Spin-aware potentials reach sub-meV accuracy on spin-lattice Hamiltonians — the precision superexchange <span class=\"math\">$J$</span> demands; ML impurity solvers are beginning to amortize DMFT's per-solve cost; and ML exchange-correlation functionals (2.8 kcal/mol ≈ 0.12 eV on molecular GMTKN55 at semilocal cost) remain unproven on solids and fail on transition metals.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"100\">[100]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"140\">[140]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"104\">[104]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"103\">[103]</sup> The &quot;solved&quot; state — quantitative <span class=\"math\">$\\lambda$</span> and <span class=\"math\">$\\omega_{\\log}$</span> with uncertainty for hydrides, computed <span class=\"math\">$J$</span> trends for cuprates — is within reach of demonstration for the hydride half only.</p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s4-4", "html": "<p>This class has the worst fabrication record in materials science, and an honest roadmap must price it. The 2020 carbonaceous-sulfur-hydride claim (288 K at ~155 GPa, <em>Nature</em>) was retracted in September 2022; the 2023 N-doped lutetium-hydride claim (294 K near ambient pressure) was retracted in November 2023 after failed replications, eight of eleven authors requesting retraction.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"114\">[114]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"141\">[141]</sup> A University of Rochester investigation concluded the senior author had engaged in &quot;falsification, fabrication, and/or plagiarism&quot;; roughly five papers were retracted and he was dismissed; a <span class=\"math\">$17 M startup built on the claims produced no reproducible result.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"142\">[142]</sup> LK-99, the 2023 social-media room-temperature claimant, failed 15+ replication attempts; floating-zone crystals showed a semiconductor, its resistivity drop traced to a Cu$</span>_2<span class=\"math\">$S impurity transition near 104 °C.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"143\">[143]</sup> Skepticism attaches to accepted results as well: Hirsch argues the hydrides' magnetic response is inconsistent with claimed type-I behavior, and Meissner confirmations remain missing for YH$</span>_6<span class=\"math\">$/YH$</span>_9<span class=\"math\">$.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"144\">[144]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"139\">[139]</sup> I read this record as a forcing function: claims here now face a post-scandal evidentiary standard, and reproducible first-principles baselines — structure, $</span>\\lambda<span class=\"math\">$, $</span>T_c<span class=\"math\">$ windows with uncertainty — are the fastest credibility firewall. The genuine discovery successes were physics, not ML: H$</span><em>3<span class=\"math\">$S and LaH$</span></em>{10}$ were predicted by ab initio structure search before synthesis.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"122\">[122]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"123\">[123]</sup></p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s4-5", "html": "<p>China's 15th Five-Year Plan (2026–2030) places superconductors and metamaterials in its frontier-materials tier; the national Outline names superconducting-magnet manufacturing a breakthrough technology for controlled fusion.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"22\">[22]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"47\">[47]</sup> Provincial plans echo it: Beijing names superconducting materials a breakthrough target, Guangdong pairs them with AI-accelerated materials R&amp;D, and Hubei names fusion HTS magnets.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"145\">[145]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"146\">[146]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"147\">[147]</sup> Operationally, the CAS Institute of Physics's first REBCO strategic report (January 2026) codifies &quot;ten key scientific and technological questions&quot; for tape scale-up — a ready-made computational problem list.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"148\">[148]</sup> On the US side, the milestone program is the anchor: <span class=\"math\">$46 M to eight companies (2023) against $</span>415 M authorized, &gt;<span class=\"math\">$350 M of private follow-on, and HTS-coil milestones already certified.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"48\">[48]</sup> The Genesis Mission adds the AI layer: challenge areas include \"Designing Materials with Predictable Functionality\" and \"Achieving AI-Driven Autonomous Laboratories,\" backed by a $</span>293 M funding opportunity.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"149\">[149]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"25\">[25]</sup> DOE's 2006 <em>Basic Research Needs for Superconductivity</em> remains the framing document.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"150\">[150]</sup> I note the alignment without triumphalism: both fund the same materials and the same simulation gap; neither owns the fix.</p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s4-6", "html": "<p>This class feeds the roadmap's superconductor discovery chain (chain 8, §15): anharmonicity-aware MLIPs plus ML-DMFT solvers → optimized hydrides/HTS and the cuprate mechanism → compact fusion magnets and lossless transmission. My sequencing judgment is firm, and it is a scope limit, not modesty: promising <span class=\"math\">$T_c$</span> prediction for cuprates is overreach, and I will not claim it for any stack I build. The defensible near-term targets are the ingredients — superexchange <span class=\"math\">$J$</span> for cuprates at cluster-DMFT fidelity; <span class=\"math\">$\\omega_{\\log}$</span>, <span class=\"math\">$\\lambda$</span>, and anharmonic dynamical stability for hydrides at SSCHA fidelity — each with a measurable right answer and an expensive method to surrogate, feeding Eliashberg <span class=\"math\">$T_c$</span> models whose output I would quote as a window with uncertainty bounds, never a point promise. The acceptance tests are concrete: reproduce the SSCHA <span class=\"math\">$\\lambda$</span> of H<span class=\"math\">$_3$</span>S to ~5% at 200 GPa (against the 43% harmonic error); hold LaH<span class=\"math\">$_{10}$</span>'s <span class=\"math\">$T_c$</span> window inside 250–260 K with anharmonicity on; rank candidates under honest LOCO error bars, not the 34–39 K fiction of random splits. Ingredient quantities, not headline temperatures, are what the downstream chains consume. The correlation problem that caps this class — Mott physics, spin degrees of freedom, the exchange-correlation ceiling — is also the defining error mode of the correlated oxides, where I turn next.</p>\n" },
]
